    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-08-04T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-08-04T03:00:00-05:00" n="1200"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1200">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.014/8–444: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-08-04T11:00:00+03:00"
                            >August 4, 1944—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2859. Full page map in press August 3 showing territory liberated by Russians
                    between June 23 and August 2 shows the Curzon Line which gives Lwow to Russia
                    and Belostok<note n="63" xml:id="d1200fn63">Bialystok.</note> to the Poles. The
                    press articles on Belostok in contrast to those on Lwow have not characterized
                    it as a Soviet town.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
